<HEAD>Thrusters Fire as Galileo Adjusts Route to Earth and Jupiter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven months into its six-year, <MONEY>$1.35
billion</MONEY> journey to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft ignited its
rocket thrusters repeatedly so it can swoop near <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in <DATE>December</DATE>,
<ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The tiny rocket thrusters were ordered to fire during a two-day
maneuver that ends late today, said <PERSON>Jim Wilson</PERSON>, a spokesman at the
<ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   ``We are changing both the speed and the aim point for our Earth
flyby. It's a very gradual change,'' mission director <PERSON>Neal Ausman</PERSON>
said <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   On <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will swoop past Earth in a gravity slingshot
maneuver designed to help expand the spacecraft's orbit around the
sun and hurl it toward its <DATE>1995</DATE> rendezvous with <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, the solar
system's largest planet.
   The spacecraft will study <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> during the flyby and again
during another slingshot maneuver in <DATE>December 1992</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> used
<PERSON>Venus</PERSON> as a gravity slingshot <DATE>Feb. 9</DATE>.
   When the maneuver started at <TIME>11:10 a.m. PDT</TIME> <DATE>Friday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was
96 million miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, but had traveled a looping path of 365
million miles since it was launched from space shuttle Atlantis
last <DATE>Oct. 18</DATE>, <PERSON>Wilson</PERSON> said.
   Its trip to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, the fifth planet from the sun, will total
2.4 billion miles.
   The <MONEY>$1.35 billion</MONEY> mission will take <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> past one asteroid in
<DATE>1991</DATE> and perhaps another in <DATE>1993</DATE>. In <DATE>July 1995</DATE>, the spacecraft
separates into a 4,890-pound orbiter and a 760-pound probe. They
are scheduled to reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Dec. 7, 1995</DATE>.
   The probe will plunge into the planet's atmosphere, relaying
measurements to the orbiter until it is destroyed by intense
atmospheric pressure. The orbiter will spend at least two years
studying and taking snapshots of <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> and its major moons Io,
<LOCATION>Europa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ganymede</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Callisto</ORGANIZATION>.
   One or two more trajectory maneuvers are needed to get <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>
to swoop about 1,000 miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in <DATE>December</DATE>, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said.
Without the maneuvers, the spacecraft would miss Earth by 1.5
million miles.
</TEXT>
