<HEAD>Jupiter-Bound Galileo Spacecraft Fires Thrusters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft, looping through
the solar system on the way to its <DATE>1995</DATE> exploration of <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>,
fired its thrusters today in a major maneuver meant to steer it
near <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> late this year.
   ``We're trying to reshape the trajectory slightly so we move
closer and closer to our aim point near <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> on <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE>,'' said
<PERSON>Neal Ausman</PERSON>, mission director at <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Jet Propulsion Laboratory</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s tiny rocket thrusters, which are small enough to fit
in the palm of a hand, started firing at <TIME>11:10 a.m. PDT</TIME> and will
fire roughly 3,000 times by the time the maneuver ends <DATE>Saturday</DATE>
<TIME>afternoon</TIME>, laboratory spokesman <PERSON>Jim Wilson</PERSON> said.
   The two-day maneuver will slow the spacecraft, which was
traveling about 66,000 mph earlier today, by about 25 mph. It also
will gradually alter its direction, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said.
   It is the second of three or four maneuvers needed to bring
<ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> within 1,000 miles of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, which will act as a gravity
slingshot to help expand the spacecraft's orbit around the sun and
propel it toward <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, he added. Without maneuvers, the
spacecraft would miss Earth by 1.5 million miles.
   As of today, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was 96 million miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, but has
traveled a looping path of 365 million miles since it was launched
from space shuttle Atlantis last <DATE>Oct. 18</DATE>. Its trip to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> will
total 2.4 billion miles.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will make a second swing past <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in <DATE>December 1992</DATE>. It
flew past <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> in another gravity slingshot maneuver on <DATE>Feb. 9</DATE>.
   In <DATE>July 1995</DATE>, the spacecraft separates into a 4,890-pound
orbiter and a 760-pound probe. They are scheduled to reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>,
the solar system's largest planet, on <DATE>Dec. 7, 1995</DATE>.
   The probe will plunge into the planet's atmosphere, relaying
measurements to the orbiter before the probe is destroyed by
intense atmospheric pressure. The orbiter will spend at least two
years studying and taking snapshots of <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> and its major moons
Europa, <LOCATION>Ganymede</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Callisto</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
