<HEAD>A List of Events During NASA's Galileo Mission to Jupiter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Galileo-Venus Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key events for the <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>
spacecraft's looping, six-year trip to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, the solar system's
largest planet:
   <DATE>Oct. 18, 1989</DATE> _ <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> is released from the cargo bay of space
shuttle Atlantis, then an <ORGANIZATION>Inertial Upper Stage</ORGANIZATION> booster launches the
spacecraft on its long voyage.
   <DATE>Nov. 9-11, 1989</DATE> _ Controllers order multiple firings of
<ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s thrusters for the first of about 30 course correction
maneuvers.
   <DATE>Dec. 22, 1989</DATE> _ Thrusters fire again for second course
correction.
   <DATE>Feb. 9, 1990</DATE> _ <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> swoops near <LOCATION>Venus</LOCATION> for its first ``gravity
assist'' maneuver, using the planet's gravity to increase the
spacecraft's speed to help it reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> makes photos
and measurements of Venus, storing them on an onboard recorder.
   Late <DATE>October 1990</DATE> _ <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> plays back to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> the photos and
measurements it made near <LOCATION>Venus</LOCATION>.
   <DATE>Dec. 8, 1990</DATE> _ <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> passes within 600 miles of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, making
photos and measurements during its second ``gravity assist''
maneuver, which will help aim it toward <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>Oct. 29, 1991</DATE> _ The spacecraft swoops within 600 miles of
asteroid Gaspra, taking pictures and measurements.
   <DATE>Dec. 8, 1992</DATE> _ <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> zooms about 185 miles above <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s
surface in the third and final ``gravity assist'' maneuver needed
to hurl it toward <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>Aug. 28, 1993</DATE> _ If <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> has adequate propellant supplies, it
passes 600 miles from asteroid Ida for photos and measurements.
   <DATE>July 1995</DATE> _ The spacecraft separates into a 760-pound <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>
probe and a 4,890-pound <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> orbiter. Both continue toward
<ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>Dec. 7, 1995</DATE> _ The probe and orbiter arrive at <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>. The
probe plunges into the planet's atmosphere, relaying measurements
to the orbiter, then is destroyed by intense atmospheric pressure.
The orbiter speeds about 600 miles from the moon Io and its
sulfur-spewing volcanoes and geysers, then goes into orbit around
<ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>December 1995-October 1997</DATE> _ The orbiter circles <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, making
photos and measurements of the giant planet and the moons <LOCATION>Europa</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Ganymede</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Callisto</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
