<HEAD>Galileo Spacecraft Making Earth Rendezvous on `Slingslot' Path to
Jupiter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft makes a
rendezvous with Earth on <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, using the planet's gravity like
a slingshot to hurl it along on its six-year journey to the solar
system's largest planet, <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   Launched in <DATE>October 1989</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will swoop about 593 miles
above the southwest <LOCATION>Atlantic Ocean</LOCATION> at <TIME>12:35 p.m. PST</TIME>.
   The pass will be monitored by mission controllers at the
<ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   During the flyby, the spacecraft will measure gases that cause
the ``greenhouse effect'' warming of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere and will
study high-altitude water vapor that helps create and destroy
Earth's ozone layer, scientists said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will also be the first spacecraft with modern
instruments to study the far side of the moon, which always faces
away from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
   On <DATE>Oct. 18, 1989</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was released from the cargo bay of
space shuttle Atlantis. Then its own rocket booster launched the
spacecraft on its long voyage, with arrival at <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> scheduled in
<DATE>1995</DATE>.
   In <DATE>February</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> neared <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> for its first ``gravity
assist'' maneuver, using the planet's gravity as a slingshot to
help it reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   Next <DATE>Oct. 29</DATE>, the spacecraft swoops within 600 miles of asteroid
Gaspra, taking pictures and measurements. Then, on <DATE>Dec. 8, 1992</DATE>,
<ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> zooms about 185 miles above <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s surface in the third
and final ``gravity assist'' maneuver needed to hurl it toward
<ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will arrive at <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Dec. 7, 1995</DATE>. The spacecraft
will orbit the planet and launch a probe to plung into its
atmosphere.
</TEXT>
