<HEAD>Computer Glitch Makes Galileo Camera Keep Snapping After Venus
Flyby</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with decision to restart camera,
attempt overnight pictures. Picks up 9th graf, `Galileo's
other...'. Should stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s camera shutter snapped
uncontrollably for five hours <DATE>Saturday</DATE> after the spacecraft zipped
around <PERSON>Venus</PERSON>, but officials said it shouldn't endanger the <MONEY>$1.35
billion</MONEY>, eight-year mission to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   Engineers at <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory shut off the
television camera while diagnosing the problem, which apparently
involved faulty software that made <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s computer send
incorrect commands to the camera, mission director <PERSON>Neal Ausman</PERSON> said.
   They decided <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> to send new computer commands to
<ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> to restart the camera so it could take a series of
photographs of Venus late <DATE>Saturday</DATE> and early <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, said <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>
spokesman <PERSON>Bob MacMillin</PERSON>.
   The engineers believed an error in computer commands they sent
to <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> made the shutter snap when it wasn't supposed to, and
they were ``pretty certain there's nothing wrong with the computer
or camera,'' he said.
   Galileo cruised around Venus at <TIME>9:59 p.m. PST</TIME> <DATE>Friday</DATE>, coming
three to four miles closer to the planet than the planned point of
closest approach 10,028 miles above the Venusian surface, said
mission science and design manager <PERSON>Bill O'Neil</PERSON>.
   The camera appeared undamaged, but its shutter opened and closed
twice per minute 468 times over five hours, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said. As
planned, only 16 pictures taken late <DATE>Friday</DATE> and early <DATE>Saturday</DATE> were
stored on <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s tape recorder, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said.
   The malfunction didn't harm those pictures, and the 452 unwanted
shutter snappings were ``just like taking pictures with no film in
the camera,'' project manager <PERSON>Dick Spehalski</PERSON> said during a <DATE>Saturday</DATE>
news conference.
   However, the problem threatened five dozen other photos the
spacecraft was supposed to take in the coming week to make a
time-lapse movie of Venus' clouds and winds, said project scientist
<PERSON>Torrence Johnson</PERSON>.
   He said scientists weren't too upset because about 20 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and
Soviet spacecraft have visited Venus previously, and the main
purpose of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s flyby was to use <PERSON>Venus</PERSON>' gravity to speed the
spacecraft for its long trip to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s other sensors will continue observing <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> as the
spacecraft speeds away from the planet, <PERSON>Spehalski</PERSON> said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was deployed <DATE>Oct. 18</DATE> from space shuttle Atlantis on a
looping 2.4-billion, six-year route that requires <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> and Earth
to be used as gravity slingshots to hurl the spacecraft to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   Once there, the spacecraft will deploy a probe to study
<ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>'s atmosphere, then orbit the giant gas planet for at least
two years in a mission that costs <MONEY>$1.35 billion</MONEY>.
   When the glitch developed at <TIME>1:41 a.m. PST</TIME> <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>
already had snapped the 16 pictures to study Venusian wind and
cloud patterns and search for lightning that might indicate
erupting volcanoes beneath the clouds.
   The camera was shut off at <TIME>6:30 a.m.</TIME> after engineers determined
it was following incorrect computer commands, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said. Eight
minutes later the erroneous commands stopped without explanation.
   Despite the trouble, ``there was no point when the spacecraft
was in jeopardy,'' he said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s TV camera is perhaps the most critical instrument on
the spacecraft. It is expected to take pictures of <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> 20 to
1,000 times more detailed than those returned by the Voyager 1 and
2 spacecraft in <DATE>1979</DATE>.
   The TV camera has a shutter, which opens to throw light on an
electronic sensor. Data from that sensor can be sent to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>,
where it is assembled into a photograph.
   ``We're dealing with a fresh spacecraft and prototype
software,'' so <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> knowingly risked a glitch in exchange for
trying to photograph Venus even though the spacecraft is still in
the shakedown part of its trip to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Johnson</PERSON> said.
   For now, the pictures and data gathered in the flyby are being
stored on <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s tape recorder, and won't be sent back to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>
until <DATE>October</DATE> when the spacecraft is close enough to transmit the
material. That antenna now can be used only for communications to
keep <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> operating.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s roundabout route to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> is an indirect result of
the <DATE>1986</DATE> explosion that destroyed the shuttle Challenger and killed
seven crew members.
   After the tragedy, the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ORGANIZATION> decided against using powerful, volatile,
liquid-fueled Centaur rockets to launch spacecraft after they were
deployed from shuttles.
   Instead, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was launched by a weaker booster after it was
released from Atlantis' cargo bay. That made it necessary to use
the gravity of Venus and Earth to help speed and aim <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> toward
<ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>. A <ORGANIZATION>Centaur</ORGANIZATION> would have propelled <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> to Venus in only
two years.
</TEXT>
