<HEAD>Galileo to Use Earth as Gravity Slingshot Dec. 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s Jupiter-bound <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft
will zoom past <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> next week, taking pictures and making
measurements as if its home planet were an alien world.
   ``It will be the first time the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> has been viewed from this
perspective. I expect it will give us a greater appreciation of
this place,'' said <PERSON>Bill O'Neil</PERSON>, project manager at the <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet
Propulsion Laboratory.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s close encounter with <ORGANIZATION>Earth</ORGANIZATION> will take place on <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE>
and is aimed at using the planet's gravity like a slingshot to send
the craft on the right path.
   The craft will swoop about 593 miles above the southwest
<LOCATION>Atlantic Ocean</LOCATION> at <TIME>12:35 p.m. PST</TIME> <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was 3.97 million
miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> today.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will be the first planetary craft to approach Earth from
space. So the flyby will be ``our first chance to look at <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> as
we have at other planets,'' <PERSON>Torrence Johnson</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s chief
scientist, said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   During its flyby, the spacecraft will measure gases that cause
the ``greenhouse effect'' warming of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere and will
study high-altitude water vapor that helps create and destroy
Earth's ozone layer, <PERSON>Johnson</PERSON> said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> also will be the first spacecraft with modern
instruments to study the far side of the moon, which is always
pointed away from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, he added.
   Galileo is powered by two nuclear batteries - not reactors -
that use the decay of radioactive plutonium to produce electricity.
   Environmentalists unsuccessfully sued to halt <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s launch
for fear the plutonium could contaminate <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere. <PERSON>O'Neil</PERSON>
said the chance that <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will somehow plunge into <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s
atmosphere and release its plutonium is less than one in <MONEY>2 million</MONEY>.
   Even if it did happen, the plutonium would cause no more than 10
cancer deaths during the next 70 years, according to <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>.
   Galileo is the most sophisticated unmanned spacecraft ever
built. It was launched from a space shuttle in <DATE>October 1989</DATE> and is
scheduled to rendezvous with <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1995</DATE> after a looping
2.4-billion-mile journey.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s route was designed so the spacecraft could use Venus
and <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> as ``gravity slingshots.'' It will use Earth for that
purpose <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE> and again in <DATE>December 1992</DATE>.
   It used <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> as a gravity slingshot last <DATE>February</DATE>. Scientists
discussed their Venus findings on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s infrared camera made the first pictures of Venus'
middle and lower cloud decks. Pictures also were used to make a
movie showing clouds moving in 150 mph winds.
   Studying <PERSON>Venus</PERSON>' acid clouds and its carbon dioxide atmosphere
may help scientists understand how increasing carbon dioxide levels
in <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere will warm the planet like glass trapping heat
in a greenhouse, said <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> astronomer <PERSON>Michael Belton</PERSON>.
</TEXT>
