<FIRST>r a PM-Neptune-Glance     08-24 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Neptune-Glance,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neptune At a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Voyager-Neptune Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some statistics known about <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> as
Voyager 2 nears the planet for its close examination tonight:
   DIAMETER: About 30,700 miles, nearly four time's <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s diameter
and the fourth largest planet after <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> and Uranus,
which is only a bit larger with a diameter of 31,760 miles.
   MOONS: Two majorones, <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> and Nereid, plus at least four
others discovered so far by Voyager 2. <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, four-fifths the size
of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s moon, is the only large moon in the solar system to orbit
a planet backwards. That suggests it once was a sun-orbiting comet
that hit a Neptunian moon and was ``captured'' into orbit around
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>.
   RINGS: So far Voyager has found <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> is orbited by one
complete ring of debris, and one ring arc, or partial ring, which
scientists believe also may prove to be a complete ring upon closer
inspection.
   DAY LENGTH: Surface wind suggests <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> takes nearly 18 hours
to spin on its axis, but <ORGANIZATION>Voyager</ORGANIZATION>'s measurements indicate a day on
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> is closer to 16 hours, the time it takes for the bulk of the
planet's interior to rotate.
   YEAR LENGTH: <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> takes 165 Earth years to make a single orbit
around the sun. That means a winter on <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> lasts more than 40
Earth years.
   DISTANCE FROM SUN: Orbits the sun at an average distance of 2.793
billion miles, 30 times as far as <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and invisible to the naked
eye from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. Neptune usually is the eighth planet from the sun,
but because of <LOCATION>Pluto</LOCATION>'s elongated orbit it is now the ninth and
outermost.
   WEATHER: A chilly 307 degrees below zero Fahrenheit at an
altitude where the atmospheric pressure is twice that at sea level
on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. Voyager has revealed cirrus-like clouds, 400-mph wind and
an Earth-sized cyclone and other storms in <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s atmosphere. The
source of the internal heat creating <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s weather is a mystery;
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s comes from decaying radioactive material in rocks.
   ATMOSPHERE: Primarily hydrogen and helium, but <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> appears
pale blue-green because enough methane, the major component of
natural gas, is present to absorb red light.
   STRUCTURE: Scientists suspect that a third of the way toward
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s center the atmosphere gives way to a slurry of water and
rock, with no distinct sky-sea boundary.
   DISCOVERY: In <DATE>1846</DATE>, by <PERSON>Johann Gottfried Galle</PERSON> and <PERSON>Heinrich Louis</PERSON>
d'Arrest at the <ORGANIZATION>Berlin Observatory</ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> was discovered because
its presence was predicted based on disturbances in Uranus' orbit.
</TEXT>
