<HEAD>Thrusters Fire as Galileo Starts First Trajectory Change on Jupiter
Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three weeks after its launch from a
shuttle, the <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft fired its thrusters <DATE>Thursday</DATE> to
begin the first of about 30 course changes needed for its
roundabout six-year trip to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``We've started the first trajectory correction maneuver,''
mission director <PERSON>Neal Ausman</PERSON> said after the three-day series of
thruster ignitions got under way at <TIME>8:31 a.m. PST</TIME>.
   During the maneuver, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> is firing four of its 12 thrusters
in a series of pulses, he said. No individual pulse exceeds two
minutes, each set of pulses takes about 45 minutes, and the entire
maneuver will be completed <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>.
   Two other thrusters may be used to correct the spacecraft's rate
of spin and the direction toward which it points, said <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON>, of
the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   The trajectory change is meant to aim <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> for its flight
past Venus in <DATE>February</DATE>. The spacecraft, launched from space shuttle
Atlantis on <DATE>Oct. 18</DATE>, will swoop by <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> once and Earth twice so
the planets can act as ``gravity slingshots'' to propel <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>
toward <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> during the <MONEY>$1.9 billion</MONEY> mission.
   On <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was about 31 million miles into its looping
2.4 billion-mile journey to the solar system's largest planet,
<PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said. It was about 4.6 million miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and 58.5
million miles from <LOCATION>Venus</LOCATION>, traveling at 60,376 mph relative to the
sun.
   In <DATE>July 1995</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will separate into an orbiter and a probe.
The orbiter will circle <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> for 22 months starting in <DATE>December
1995</DATE>, the same month the probe will parachute into the Jovian
atmosphere, making measurements for 75 minutes until it is crushed
by intense pressure.
   About 30 course corrections involving thruster firings spread
over 135 days will be required en route to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> has ignited its 3.5 inch-long thrusters on other
occasions, but those firings were to adjust spin or direction,
<PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said. The three-day maneuver that started <DATE>Thursday</DATE> is
<ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s first trajectory correction, he added.
   <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said the West German-built thrusters have to fire in
pulses to avoid contaminating sensitive parts of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>. The
thrusters are attached to the spinning part of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>, and can
fire only when they are not above sensitive areas on the
non-spinning section of the spacecraft.
   The thrusters also are fired in pulses because <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> fears
continuous firing might make them overheat and burn through, a
problem that developed on the same type of thrusters on two
satellites in recent years, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
